{[%evp 0,43,19,31,57,57,89,48,48,44,44,41,64,54,58,20,72,71,71,71,65,39,75,60, 40,53,113,69,89,73,81,53,59,26,18,17,19,15,21,20,54,27,16,13,90,15]} 1. e4 Nf6 {The Alekhine Defence has never been considered as one of the first-rate openings, but it should not be underestimated, either. Black's idea is to provoke White into overextending his central pawns, so that they could be attacked and undermined more easily later. Therefore, White should exercise caution when pushing the central pawns and make sure that they are always well-protected. If he manages to do that, he can usually count on an advantage out of the opening as he typically controls more space.} 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 {The repertoire against the Alekhine Defence that I suggest is based on this Modern variation. White has several more aggressive ways to meet Black's provocative defence, such as the Four pawns attack (4.c4 Nb6 5.f4) and Chase variation (3.c4 Nb6 4.c5) , as well as the Classical variation (4.c4 Nb6 5.exd6) . The advantage of 4.Nf3 over the previously mentioned variations is that it allows White to keep the space advantage in the centre without overextending his pawns, which, as mentioned above, is one of the main ideas behind Black's provocative opening strategy. A notable upside of postponing the tempting c2-c4 move is that we can develop the bishop to this square in some variations, thereby putting pressure on the black knight on d5 and keeping the d4-pawn solidly protected with c2-c3 if need be. Compared to the other variations, Black has more defensive schemes at his disposal in response to 4.Nf3, yet White typically keeps a solid positional edge against any try by Black. In the next 8 chapters, we will go over the most common black defences. In this one, we will look at the move} Bg4 {which has historically been the main continuation for Black, although it is not as popular in modern times. Developing the bishop while creating a pin on Nf3 is very sensible indeed. White also has a natural and good response in} 5. Be2 {The main move in this position is} e6 {as Black makes way for the other bishop.} ( {The alternative is} Nc6 {as usual in the Alekhine Defence, Black creates pressure on white centre with this developing knight move.} 6. O-O dxe5 ( e6 {would transpose into the position that arises in the main line with Black playing 6.. .Nc6. However, this setup allows White to drive out the knights with c4-d5 and begin to seize the initiative.} 7. c4 Nb6 8. exd6 cxd6 9. d5 $1 {The principled continuation. White obtains an advantage after} exd5 10. cxd5 Bxf3 11. Bxf3 Ne5 12. Be2 $14 {The space advantage and the bishop pair are strong positional assets in this type of structure.} Be7 13. a4 {A typical idea with the knight on b6. White begins to seize space on the queenside.} O-O ( a5 {stops the expansion, but allows} 14. Bb5+ Ned7 15. Ra3 $1 {A strong manoeuvre! The rook will be relocated to the kingside, helping to create an attack on the king.} O-O 16. Rh3 g6 17. Bh6 Re8 18. Be3 $16  ) 14. a5 Nbd7 15. Nc3 {Fabiano Caruana gave a good example of how to increase the advantage in this type of middlegame in the following instructive game:} a6 16. Be3 Rc8 17. Qb3 Qc7 18. Rfc1 Qb8 19. f4 Ng6 20. g3 $16 {black pieces were pushed back into passivity in Caruana, F (2662) -Galindo Rodriguez,F (2237) Montcada 2009 1-0 (65)}  ) 7. Nxe5 $1 {This active move implies a pawn sacrifice, but it is the critical test of Black's opening strategy. For the pawn, White strongly centralizes the knight while Black has problems with his development.} Bxe2 ( Nxe5 {is not principled. White gets a very pleasant space advantage after both} 8. dxe5 Bf5 ( {and} Bxe2 9. Qxe2 Qd7 10. c4 Nb6 11. Nc3 e6 12. Rd1 Qc6 13. b3 Bb4 14. Ne4 Be7 15. Qg4 $16  ) 9. c4 Nb6 10. Qb3 e6 11. Rd1 Qc8 12. Qg3 c6 13. Nc3 Qc7 14. Bf4 $16  ) 8. Qxe2 Nxd4 9. Qc4 {The initiative is firmly in White's hands now.} f6 {Black should deal with the strong knight sooner than later.} ( c5 {is very risky for Black in the view of} 10. Rd1 b5 ( {The problem for Black is that} e6 {runs into} 11. Rxd4 $1 cxd4 12. Qb5+ Ke7 13. Qxb7+ Qc7 14. Qxa8 Qxe5 15. Qxa7+ Kf6 16. Nd2 Qe1+ 17. Nf1 $18  ) 11. Qxc5 Nf4 {This is a clever tactical riposte, but White can even accept the challenge with} 12. Rxd4 $1 Ne2+ 13. Kf1 Nxd4 14. Be3 f6 15. Bxd4 fxe5 16. Qc6+ Kf7 17. Qf3+ $18 {followed by Bxe5. Black's development is non-existent.}  ) 10. Qxd4 fxe5 11. Qxe5 Qd6 12. Qe2 {Of course, White keeps the queens on the board. A superior pawn structure and easier development give him a clear positional advantage.} O-O-O 13. Nd2 {This is the most precise move. The knight can use d2 as a springboard to many good squares (c4, e4, f3) , depending on opponent's actions.} ( {Black managed to hold a slightly worse, but solid endgame in the following GM encounter:} 14. c4 Nb4 15. Nc3 Qg6 16. Be3 Nc6 17. Rad1 Rxd1 18. Rxd1 e6 19. Nb5 a6 20. Nd4 Nxd4 21. Bxd4 Be7 $14 {1/2 (42) Stevic,H (2610) -Narciso Dublan,M (2530) Rijeka 2010}  ) e6 ( {The alternative is} g6 14. Qg4+ Kb8 15. Nf3 $16 {when 16.Ng5 is quite an unpleasant threat to meet.}  ) 14. Nc4 Qa6 15. Bg5 $16 {White pieces are placed actively. The weak pawn on e6 gives White a basis for a pleasant long-term advantage.}  ) ( c6 {transposes to Chapter 7.}  ) 6. O-O Be7 7. h3 {A useful move. White would like to determine the position of the black bishop. This idea is quite common in such structures.} Bh5 {Black should retreat with the bishop. The exchange on f3 would give White a comfortable position.} ( Bxf3 $6 {Black does not get anything in return for the bishop pair, as we can see in the following variations:} 8. Bxf3 Nc6 ( dxe5 $2 9. c4 $1 Nb6 10. Bxb7 exd4 11. Bxa8 Nxa8 12. Qa4+ Nd7 13. Qxa7 $18  ) ( c6 9. c4 Nc7 10. exd6 Qxd6 11. Nc3 O-O 12. Be3 $16  ) 9. exd6 Qxd6 10. c4 ( 11. c3 $5 O-O 12. Nd2 $16 {is also good, not providing any targets in the centre.}  ) Nf6 11. Be3 O-O 12. Qd2 Rad8 13. Rd1 $16 {White is fully in control of the position.}  ) 8. c4 {A logical continuation. White drives out the knight from an active central position and begins the fight for the central squares. At the same time, this move facilitates the development of his remaining minor pieces.} Nb6 9. Nc3 {It is preferable to maintain the tension in the centre, even though 9.exd6 is also a reasonable choice, as well.} O-O 10. Be3 {White completed development of his pieces and strengthened the central pawns. Thus, his opening advantage should not be in doubt. At this point, we have also reached the tabiya of this variation. Black has a variety of options, so let us take a look at the most notable ones.} d5 {This is by far the most popular choice for Black and also a fairly typical idea in the Alekhine Defence. The idea is to close the position in the centre and create a pawn chain f7-e6-d5, which is not easy for White to destroy. The downside of this strategy is a lack of operating space for black pieces as White claims a big space advantage after the principled answer 11.c5.} ( Nc6 {Is a common alternative. White can confidently employ the familiar idea:} 11. exd6 cxd6 12. d5 $1 {Not only chasing the knight away from c6 but more importantly, fixing the central pawn structure and creating a weakness on d6.} exd5 ( Bxf3 13. Bxf3 Ne5 14. dxe6 fxe6 {Black is hoping for some typical counterplay against the c4-pawn, but} 15. Bg4 $1 {keeps White firmly in the driver's seat.} Nxg4 16. Qxg4 Rf6 17. Rac1 Rc8 18. b3 $16  ) 13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. Qxd5 Bg6 15. Rad1 $16  ) ( N8d7 {is a sensible option. Black forces the exchange of pawns in the centre without allowing White to push d4-d5 with a tempo. At the same time, he wants to direct the knight toward a good f6-square. Still, after} 11. exd6 cxd6 12. b3 {White retains a comfortable space advantage, which provides him with better manoeuvring options. Below are some typical ways in which the middlegame battle can continue:} Rc8 {The waiting strategy is probably Black's best bet in such positions.} ( a5 {This weakens the b5-square.} 13. Qd2 Nf6 14. Rfe1 h6 15. d5 e5 16. Rad1 $16 {with good attacking prospects on the kingside in Short,N-Enkhtuul,A 2018 BCC Open 1-0}  ) ( Nf6 {is a sensible manoeuvre with the idea to improve the b6-knight. However, after} 13. Rc1 Nbd7 14. g4 $1 Bg6 15. Nh4 d5 16. Nxg6 hxg6 17. Bf3 Qa5 18. c5 $16 {White dominates on both wings.}  ) 13. Rc1 a6 14. Re1 Re8 15. a4 Nf8 16. d5 e5 17. Qd2 $16  ) ( {The exchanging operation} dxe5 11. Nxe5 Bxe2 12. Qxe2 {favours White as he has full central control and Black struggles with a lack of space.} N8d7 13. Rad1 Nxe5 14. dxe5 Qe8 15. Qg4 Kh8 16. b3 $16  ) 11. c5 {Besides this critical reply} ( 12. cxd5 $5 {also deserves attention. This leads to a more open type of position in which White can keep the initiative with precise play.} Nxd5 ( exd5 {leads to a solid, but inferior pawn structure for Black. White has a nice manoeuvre at his disposal:} 13. Ne1 $1 {sending the knight to d3 and preparing the march of the f-pawn.} Bxe2 14. Qxe2 c6 15. Nd3 Na6 16. b3 $14  ) 13. Qb3 {An important move, allowing White to continues the fight for the central squares.} ( 14. Nxd5 Qxd5 15. Rc1 Qd7 16. a3 Rd8 $132  ) {The endgame after} Nc6 ( Nxe3 14. fxe3 {After this exchange, White has strengthened this centre and obtained prospects for active play on the f-file.} Nc6 15. Rad1 Nb4 16. g4 $1 Bg6 17. e4 $16  ) 14. Nxd5 Qxd5 15. Qxd5 exd5 16. Rac1 $14 {is favourable for White, especially in the view of the following resource:} f6 17. Ba6 $1 Rfb8 ( bxa6 18. Rxc6 $16  ) 18. g4 Bg6 19. Be2 $16  ) Bxf3 {An important intermediate move, quite typical for the whole opening. Black wants to deflect the bishop from controlling the c4-square so that the knight could get there. However, we do not have to oblige.} ( {Instead,} N6d7 {leaves Black in a cramped position after} 12. b4 a6 13. Ne1 $1 Bxe2 14. Qxe2 Nc6 15. Nd3 g6 16. f4 $16  ) {The best move is a somewhat unexpected} 12. gxf3 {White voluntarily destroys his pawn structure, but there are also a couple of downsides. Of course, the immediate benefit is the fact that we retain control over the c4-square, forcing the black knight to a passive square. Secondly, this move opens the g-file that we can use to attack the black king.} ( 13. Bxf3 $5 {used to be considered inaccurate in the pre-computer era. However, according to Stockfish, this continuation is also playable. White retains a healthy pawn structure and gets an advantage after} Nc4 14. Bf4 {The point is that Black is in time to undermine white pawn chain with} b6 ( Nxb2 $2 {is bad in the view of} 15. Qb1 Nc4 16. Qxb7 Nd7 17. Nxd5 $1 {destroying black pawn center.} exd5 18. Qxd5 $18  ) 15. b3 Na5 16. Rb1 {This is the key move. This way, White indirectly defends the pawn on c5 and keeps the black knight on the edge of the board.} bxc5 ( Nbc6 17. Na4 bxc5 18. dxc5 Rb8 19. Be2 Bg5 20. Bh2 g6 21. f4 Bh6 22. Qd2 $14  ) 17. dxc5 Nbc6 18. a3 Bg5 19. Bh2 Qe7 20. Na4 $14  ) Nc8 {The idea behind this move is to eventually manoeuvre the knight toward f5-square now that White cannot play g4 any more. Other knight retreats are bad for Black.} ( {In case of} Nc4 13. Bxc4 dxc4 14. Qe2 {Black loses the c-pawn without sufficient compensation.} c6 15. Qxc4 Na6 16. Ne4 Nc7 $16  ) ( {After} N6d7 13. f4 {Black is virtually forced to play} f5 ( {since} Bh4 {now runs into} 14. f5 $1  ) 14. b4 a6 15. Kh2 {White enjoys a large space advantage. The plan is to combine pressure on both flanks, making Black's defence more difficult.} Nc6 16. Rb1 Bh4 17. Rg1 Qe7 18. a4 $16  ) 13. f4 {White improves his pawn structure and in some cases threatens to play f5, so Black needs to be on guard.} Bh4 {This is the logical continuation of the knight manoeuvre on the previous move as Black frees the e7-square for the knight.} ( Nc6 {is a common alternative, setting up a tricky ...Bxc5, dxc5 d4 tactic. Now I believe that White should play} 14. Bd3 {which not only aims at the kingside but also indirectly prevents Black's main idea.} ( {In one GM game, White allowed the abovementioned tactic by playing} 15. Kh2 Bxc5 16. dxc5 d4 17. Ne4 dxe3 18. fxe3 {but his advantage in the endgame after} Qxd1 19. Raxd1 N8e7 $14 {was only minimal. 1-0 (44) Motylev,A (2676) -Appel,R (2535) Germany 2014}  ) ( 15. b4 $5 {also deserves attention as the b-pawn is indirectly defended.}  ) g6 {This is the least weakening way to prevent f4-f5.} ( {Black cannot play} Bxc5 $2 15. dxc5 d4 {because of} 16. Bxh7+ $1 Kxh7 17. Qh5+ Kg8 18. Ne4 $1 {and White achieves a decisive attack:} f6 19. Kh2 $1 dxe3 20. Rg1 exf2 21. Nxf2 Rf7 22. Rad1 Qe7 23. Ng4 $18  ) ( f5 {closes is an alternative, but an important difference compared to the main line is that after} 15. Kh2 Bh4 {White has} 16. Qh5 $1 {which disrupts coordination of black pieces.} Kh8 ( {The point is that Black cannot expel the queen from h5 with} g6 {at once because of} 17. Rg1 Kg7 18. Rg2 $18 {with a powerful attack on the g-file.}  ) 17. Rg1 Rg8 18. a3 a5 19. Rab1 g6 {Black eventually manages to expel the queen, but this has cost him some precious time. White keeps a solid positional advantage after} 20. Qe2 $16  ) 15. Kh2 Kh8 16. Rg1 {We may even allow Black to play} Bxc5 17. dxc5 d4 {since after} 18. Ne4 dxe3 19. fxe3 $16 {he cannot favourably trade queens as in Motylev-Appel game, so White keeps attacking chances in the middlegame.}  ) 14. Bd3 {Logically, White activates the bishop and prepares the f4-f5 breakthrough.} g6 {As noted in a similar variation above, this is the less committal of the two ways that Black can prevent f4-f5.} ( {The main alternative is} f5 {which leads to a very solid position for Black, but also a one where he lacks any active counterplay. White should try to make a breakthrough on the queenside and combine it with the pressure via the g-file. A possible continuation is} 15. b4 a6 16. a4 Ne7 17. b5 Ng6 18. Kh2 Be7 19. Be2 Nh4 20. Qb3 $16  ) ( Ne7 $2 {is bad because of} 15. Qg4 Ng6 16. f5 exf5 17. Bxf5 $18 {with a strategically winning position for White.}  ) 15. Qg4 $1 {A precise move. White does not allow the knight to be relocated to f5.} ( 16. Kh2 $6 Ne7 $132  ) Kh8 16. Kh2 f5 {Black needs to block the pawn structure on the kingside at once. Otherwise, White himself wanted to sacrifice a pawn with f4-f5 to create a strong initiative.} ( {For instance,} Nc6 {would be met by} 17. f5 $1 exf5 ( gxf5 18. Qh5 $18 {with 19.Rg1 and Nc3-e2-f4 coming next.}  ) 18. Qf4 Re8 19. a3 b6 20. b4 $18 {coordination of black pieces is very bad and the d5-pawn weak. White is strategically winning.}  ) 17. Qe2 Nc6 {By provoking . ..f7-f5, White has ensured that Black does not have access to f5-outpost. Now, it is time to grab the initiative on the queenside.} 18. a3 Rg8 {Seeking counterplay with ...g6-g5 break.} ( {In case of} a5 19. Rab1 N8e7 20. Rg1 $16 {keeps White in control. Black would only make things worse if he would play} b6 21. cxb6 cxb6 22. Rbc1 {when opening of the position would favour his opponent.}  ) 19. Rg1 {Not giving a chance for counterplay.} b6 {This is the only active option for Black, otherwise he would be suffering in a position with no active possibilities. Opening the position with} 20. cxb6 $5 {makes the most sense now. White keeps a pleasant advantage with} axb6 21. Rac1 Nb8 22. b4 $16  *

