{[%evp 0,31,5,23,113,83,57,57,50,64,91,39,43,26,18,29,-2,-11,-6,-7,43,33,58,40, 54,57,43,29,64,64,55,51,51,53]} 1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 g6 {This continuation has gained popularity for Black recently. The fianchetto of king's bishop is an important strategy in the Alekhine's defence as a way to put pressure on White's pawn centre, similarly to another hypermodern opening, the Grunfeld Defence.} 5. Bc4 {This is the best move in the position. White activates the bishop with a tempo to a diagonal from which it will create pressure on the kingside. This is one of the advantages of keeping c2-c4 move in reserve, compared to the 4. c4 variation.} Nb6 {This continuation is the most in the spirit of this opening.} ( c6 {deserves attention as the knight remains in the centre, blocking bishop's sight to f7-square. However, its major downside is that it is not in line with Black's strategy to attack white pawn centre in the most effective way with ...Nc6 and ...Bg7.} 6. exd6 $5 {This is a good moment for this exchange as it forces Black to take the pawn with the queen instead of the pawn. White's plan is to use the opening of the e-file in his favour to attack the e7-pawn.} ( {Also possible is} 7. O-O Bg7 8. Re1 O-O 9. h3 dxe5 10. Nxe5 Nd7 11. Nf3 $14 {although here White does not have time to organize quick pressure on the e-pawn.}  ) Qxd6 ( exd6 $2 {is plain bad because Black is not ready to open to e-file with the king still on e8.} 7. O-O Bg7 8. Re1+ Be6 9. Ng5 Qd7 10. Qg4 $18  ) 7. O-O Bg7 8. Re1 O-O 9. Bg5 {The most natural continuation, developing the bishop and putting pressure on the backward pawn.} Bg4 {This is the strongest reply for Black as he takes the opportunity to swap off his 'bad' bishop.} ( {A passive move like} Re8 {would provide White with enough time to prevent ...Bg4 with} 10. h3 b5 11. Bb3 a5 12. a4 $16 {In such a position, Black is facing a typical strategic problem of the useless light-squared bishop.}  ) 10. Nbd2 {White needs to just keep developing} ( {since} 11. Bxd5 $6 Qxd5 12. Bxe7 Re8 $132 {gives Black too much counterplay for the pawn.}  ) e6 11. h3 Bxf3 12. Nxf3 {White wins the bishop pair, which provides him with a small but stable advantage. Black can solidify the position of the centralized knight with} Nd7 13. c3 b5 14. Bf1 $14 {but there is no doubt that chances are on White's side in such positions.}  ) 6. Bb3 Bg7 7. Qe2 $5 {This solid, center-strengthening move should be preferred} ( {over the aggressive alternative} 8. Ng5 {which has been the most popular move in this position. While the early attack on the vulnerable f7-square has its merits, Black has found a forced way to a safe position:} e6 9. Qf3 Qe7 {An important move. Black is not in a hurry to castle, instead of aiming to create pressure on the e5-pawn.} 10. Ne4 dxe5 11. Bg5 Qb4+ 12. c3 Qa5 {and now the best that White can get is an optically better endgame with} 13. Bf6 Bxf6 14. Qxf6 O-O 15. Qxe5 Qxe5 16. dxe5 {but here Black gradually equalizes after} Bd7 $1 17. Nbd2 Bc6 18. O-O-O N8d7 19. f4 a5 20. Rhe1 Kg7 $11  ) O-O ( {Black can also release the tension in the centre with} dxe5 8. dxe5 {when White needs to carefully protect his e-pawn to keep better chances.} O-O ( {Quick assaults on the e-pawn do not work well} Nc6 9. Nc3 Nd4 10. Nxd4 Qxd4 11. f4 $16  ) ( {and} Bg4 $4 9. Bxf7+ Kxf7 10. Ng5+ $18  ) 9. h3 {An important preventive move. Black already threatened to play Bg4, create an unpleasant pin and undermining defence of the central pawn.} a5 {The idea behind this move is not only to harass the powerful b3-bishop but also to activate the knight via a6-c5, something that we do not see in other lines.} 10. a4 {is the right response. White should fix the a-pawns and not give Black the opportunity to develop the rook through a5.} Na6 11. Nc3 Nc5 12. Be3 Nxb3 13. Rd1 $1 {This the intermediate move is crucial to worsen the position of the opponent's queen.} ( 14. cxb3 Be6 15. Rd1 Nd5 16. Nd4 Qc8 $11  ) Qe8 14. Bxb6 $1 {Another important intermezzo before taking on b3.} ( 15. cxb3 Be6 16. Nd4 Bd5 17. O-O Rd8 $11  ) cxb6 ( {Black achieves little with} Nc1 15. Rxc1 cxb6 16. O-O Qc6 17. Rfd1 Be6 18. Rd4 Rac8 19. Rcd1 $14 {White has an even better pawn structure here compared to the main line.}  ) 15. cxb3 Be6 16. Nd4 Qc8 17. O-O $14 {This is a typical case where the well-centralized knights on strong outposts are superior to the bishop pair. White's chances are preferable.}  ) ( {As usual, the premature pin} Bg4 $4 {loses to} 8. Bxf7+ $1 Kxf7 9. Ng5+ Kg8 10. Qxg4 $18  ) 8. h3 {Having castled, Black already threatened to create an unpleasant pin with ...Bg4, so this preventive measure is neccessary.} Nc6 {A typical piece development in this structure as Black puts pressure on the centre, while at the same time keeping an option to play ... Na5 and exchange the strong bishop.} ( {The main alternative is} c5 {attacking the centre with a pawn.} 9. dxc5 dxc5 10. O-O c4 $5 {This is interesting pawn sacrifice is the point behind Black's previous move. In return for the pawn, he gains the bishop pair advantage and quick piece development.} 11. Bxc4 Nxc4 12. Qxc4 Nc6 13. Re1 Be6 14. Qe2 Bd5 ( {White keeps a healthy extra pawn after a slower move like} Rc8 15. c3 Bd5 16. Nbd2 $16  ) 15. Nc3 ( 16. Nbd2 $6 Nb4 $1 $132  ) Bxf3 16. Qxf3 Bxe5 {Black regained the pawn, but White obtains the initiative in turn with} 17. Bh6 Bg7 ( Re8 18. Rad1 Qc8 19. Nd5 Bxb2 20. c3 Ba3 21. g4 $16  ) 18. Bxg7 Kxg7 19. Rad1 Qb6 20. b3 Rad8 21. Nd5 Qc5 22. c4 $14 {The knight on d5 takes a powerful position and limits Black's possibilities.}  ) ( a5 9. a4 dxe5 10. dxe5 Na6 11. O-O {transposes to 7... dxe5 variation.}  ) 9. O-O Na5 {This is a favourable exchange for Black, although it does not mean that he has solved all of his opening problems with it. His bishops and the knight on b6 remain quite passive.} ( {A typical alternative is} dxe5 10. dxe5 Nd4 11. Nxd4 Qxd4 12. Re1 {when White enjoys a clear advantage thanks to better central control. Possible continuations are:} a5 ( Be6 13. Bxe6 fxe6 14. Nd2 Rf5 15. Nf3 Qc4 16. Qe4 Qxe4 17. Rxe4 $16  ) ( Bf5 13. Nc3 Rae8 $2 14. a4 $1 Qd8 15. a5 Na8 16. Bf4 c6 17. Qe3 a6 18. Bh6 Qc8 19. Ra4 $1 {Thanks to this strong manoeuvre, White relocates the rook to the kingside and creates a decisive kingside attack.} Be6 20. Rh4 $18 {Efimenko,Z-Reinemer,F 2019 Drezden-Open 1-0}  ) 13. a4 Bd7 {The bishop is placed best on c6.} 14. c3 Qh4 15. e6 Bxe6 16. Bxe6 fxe6 17. Nd2 $14  ) ( Bf5 10. Nc3 Na5 11. Re1 {usually leads to a similar position to the main line.}  ) ( d5 $6 {is a rather passive alternative. Black closes the centre but loses the flexibility of his pawn structure, giving White a clear space advantage.} 10. c3 f6 11. Bf4 fxe5 12. Bxe5 Nxe5 13. Nxe5 e6 14. Nd2 Qd6 15. Rfe1 $16  ) 10. Nc3 {The knight is naturally headed toward the central square e4.} Nxb3 ( {Black could deny this plan with} d5 {but then White goes} 11. Bf4 c6 12. Nd1 $1 {which is a typical way to relocate the c3-knight in this structure.} h6 13. Ne3 g5 14. Bh2 Nxb3 15. axb3 f5 16. exf6 exf6 17. c3 Qe7 18. Rfe1 Re8 19. Qd3 $14 {In this symmetrical pawn structure, White is fully in control thanks to much more active pieces.}  ) 11. axb3 Bf5 {The best square for the bishop, as it creates pressure on the c2-pawn while also enabling the exchange for the knight on the e4-square in some cases.} ( f6 {is a possibility now that the bishop is not on b3 any more, but Black does not manage to seriously oppose white centre with it, as can be seen in the following variation} 12. Re1 fxe5 13. dxe5 Bf5 14. Be3 $5 dxe5 15. Bc5 $16  ) 12. Re1 {This move is often useful with the pawn on e5. White is not in any rush and can slowly centralize his pieces and support his pawn centre, waiting to see how Black will proceed.} ( {White was less successful with a more direct} 13. Ne4 Qd7 ( a5 $5 14. Ng3 Bd7 15. Bf4 a4 $132  ) 14. Ng3 a6 15. Re1 h6 16. Nh4 e6 17. Ne4 Bxe4 18. Qxe4 dxe5 19. dxe5 Qd5 20. Qe2 Qb5 $11 {1/2 (52) Adams,M (2694) -Zhukova,N (2462) Caleta 2010}  ) h6 {With this move, Black is ready to meet White's natural continuation 13.Bf4 with 13...g5, followed by ...Bg6, etc.} ( Qd7 {is a straightforward way to connect the rooks, but then White can simply continue} 13. Bf4 $16 {with harmonious piece coordination and domination in the centre. Black bishop might find itself in trouble if White could play d4-d5 next with the g2-g4 trapping threat.}  ) ( c6 13. Bf4 a5 14. g4 $1 Bd7 15. Ne4 Nd5 16. Bg3 $16  ) 13. Nh4 ( 14. Ne4 $5 {as in Adams' game above, also deserves attention as Re1 for White is a more useful move than ...h6 for Black.}  ) e6 ( Bd7 $2 {allows} 14. e6 $1 Bxe6 15. Nxg6 fxg6 16. Qxe6+ $18  ) 14. Nxf5 exf5 15. f4 c6 16. Be3 $14 {and White keep better chances thanks to a long-lasting space advantage.}  *

