re.}  ) a6 16. a4 Re8 17. Qd3 {White can slowly improve his position, while Black has to wait passively.} Nf8 18. Rfd1 Qd7 19. Rab1 $14  ) 13. Nxg6 {It is the right time to make this exchange since the black bishop has left the h2-b8 diagonal. White gets the advantage of two bishops, although Black's position remains solid.} ( {In the game against Kopylov, I continued} 14. Bf4 {instead, which could have transposed into the main line if my opponent had continued} O-O ( {Instead, he chose the inferior} Nd5 $6 15. Nxd5 exd5 16. Nxg6 hxg6 17. Re1 O-O {1-0 (48) Efimenko,Z (2636) -Kopylov,M (2424) Germany 2017 and now} 18. Qb3 $16 {would have lead to a better version of the main line for White as Re1 is a more useful move than Bf3.}  ) 15. Nxg6 hxg6 16. Bf3 {etc.}  ) hxg6 14. Bf4 O-O 15. Bf3 $5 {White improves the position of the light-squared bishop and naturally plans to push the queenside pawns forward to create a weakness on c6 or b7.} ( 16. b4 {might be slightly premature since after} a6 17. a4 Nd5 18. Nxd5 exd5 {White cannot put direct pressure on b7-pawn any more. White's position is only very slightly better. For example:} 19. Qd2 Re8 20. Rfe1 Nf8 21. Be3 Ne6 22. Rab1 Ng5 23. Rb3 Ne4 24. Qc1 Bf6 25. g3 $14  ) Nd5 {The most logical continuation as Black occupies the d5-outpost and plans to put pressure on the d4 pawn with ...Bf6.} ( Re8 16. Qb3 Qc8 17. Rfe1 $14 {is rather passive for Black and he would need to play ...Nd5 sooner or later to secure some extra space for his pieces.}  ) 16. Nxd5 exd5 17. Qb3 $1 {This is the reason why we have postponed the thematic b2-b4-b5 attack. By attacking the queenside pawns directly, we are likely to force a concession from Black without having to push the pawns altogether.} b6 {Black is more or less forced to weaken his pawn structure.} ( Qc8 {is a passive move. The queen is too strong a piece to defend the pawn on b7. Moreover, it runs into an unpleasant pin:} 18. Rae1 Re8 19. Bg4 $1 $36  ) 18. cxb6 Nxb6 {The most active cont