 12. Nc3 a6 13. b4 $1 {preparing the breakthrough on the c5-square, after all.} b6 {Black should keep the position closed.} ( {In case of} cxb4 14. c5+ Kxc5 15. Na4+ Kd6 {White wins back the piece with a nice knight manoeuvre} 16. Nb2 $1 $18  ) ( Qb6 14. Rc1 $1 g5 ( Qxb4 15. Bd3 g5 16. Bg3 $18  ) 15. Bg3 Bf5 16. Bd3 {1-0 (16) Manca,F (2424) -Sulskis,S (2586) Ortisei 2012}  ) 14. Bd3 $1 {White can calmly complete his development as the pin on e5 paralyzes Black.} g6 {A clever idea, trying to deflect white bishop with ...Bh6 and prepare ...Rf8 to trap the queen. However, White has a brilliant solution:} 15. bxc5+ bxc5 16. Rb1 Bh6 17. Rb7 $3 {A fantastic move! The threat is Qxf6 and Ne4#, while the rook is immune due to Qe6+.} Bd7 ( Bxf4 18. Qxf6+ $1 exf6 19. Ne4#  ) ( Bxb7 18. Qe6+ Kc7 19. Bxe5+ Qd6 20. Qxe7+ Nd7 21. Qxd6+ $18  ) 18. Bg3 Rb8 ( {In case of} Rf8 {White has another brilliant resource} 19. Qxh7 $3 $18 Nxh7 20. Ne4#  ) 19. Rxb8 Qxb8 20. O-O $1 {Bringing reinforcements!} ( 21. Bxe5+ $2 {does not work on the account of} Kxe5 22. Qxe7+ Kd4 23. Qxf6+ Kxd3 24. O-O Rf8 25. Qe7 Qe8 $19  ) Qf8 21. Re1 $1 {The point. With such an exposed black king, it is not surprising that White has such resources.} Nfg4 22. Qf3 $1 Qxf3 23. gxf3 $18  ) ( {The queen exchange} Qe8 {brings no relief to Black, either.} 12. Qxe8 Nxe8 13. Nc3 Bf5 14. c5+ Kxc5 15. Bxe5 $18  ) {However, White gets the piece back with a superior endgame with the thematic} 12. c5+ $1 Kxc5 13. Bxe5 Qxd5 14. Qxd5+ Kxd5 15. Bxc7 $16 {when black king is a little bit too centralized for its own good.}  ) 6. Bc4 $5 {Since Black has already shown that he does not plan to play ...Bf5, ...e6 setup, it makes a lot of sense to develop the bishop to this diagonal, just as we did in response to 4.. .g6 in Chapter 2.} ( 7. c4 {is less principled now because after} Nb6 8. Nc3 Bg7 9. Be3 {Black could play} c5 {in one go, compared to a similar position from Chapter 4 where Black lost a tempo on 5...c6. This option to allows him to immediately undermine white centre, so the alternative 6.Bc4 seems more principled from White's point of view.}  ) c6 {This typical move is the most common here,} ( {but we need to mention a trendy line} Be6 $5 {which was recently employed by no less than the World Champion himself. The main difference compared to the similar variation from the previous chapter is that Black does not spend time on the solidifying move ... c7-c6, but rather plans to push the c-pawn one square further to strike at the white centre.} 7. O-O Bg7 ( {In one game, Carlsen began with} Nd7 {but this move can be well met with} 8. Nf3 $1 $146 ( {Instead,} 9. Re1 {as played by Wesley So, is rather tame. Carlsen solved all opening problems after the favourable exchange of knights:} Nxe5 10. Rxe5 Bg7 11. Re1 O-O $11 {Moreover, after} 12. Bb3 {he quickly took over the initiative thanks to a thematic pawn break} a5 $1 13. a4 c5 $1 14. dxc5 Nb4 $132 {0-1 (64) So,W (2770) -Carlsen,M (2863) chess24.com INT 2020}  ) {9.Ng5 is a serious threat, so Black does not have a great choice:} Ne3 9. Bxe3 Bxc4 10. Re1 {Despite winning the bishop pair, the black position is inferior as White has a huge lead in development.} Bg7 11. Nbd2 Ba6 {A sad necessity. The bishop is misplaced there, but there was no better choice.} 12. Bg5 Nf6 13. c4 $16  ) 8. Re1 O-O 9. Nd2 {This developing move, preferred by top GMs Grischuk and Dominguez is the most precise.} ( {In case of} 10. Bb3 {Black could again seek counterplay with Carlsen's operation:} a5 $5 11. a4 c5 $1 $132  ) Nd7 10. Nef3 $1 {Of course, White does not want to exchange the knights as it would help Black gain more space for his pieces. It is important than the bishop on c4 is defended by Nd2, so that Black does not have ...Ne/c3 tactics.} N7f6 $6 {This dubious move was played in the only GM game in this position.} ( {However, the critical continuation is} c6 $5 {when we get a position that is very similar to the main line 6...c6. White would have to continue in a positional manner} 11. c3 ( {The exchange sacrifice from Grischuk's game} 12. Rxe6 fxe6 13. Ng5 {does not work nearly as well now because of Black's counterplay with} Qb6 $1 14. Nxe6 Bxd4 $132  ) b5 12. Bb3 Nc7 13. Ne4 $14 {With a typical slight edge for White thanks to a space advantage. However, this is a playable position for Black, as well, leading into an interesting middlegame fight.}  ) {The problem is that it allows a thematic exchange sacrifice:} 11. Rxe6 $1 fxe6 12. Ng5 Qd6 13. Qe1 $1 {White soon obtained a winning position.} b5 14. Bb3 a5 15. a4 bxa4 16. Nc4 Qc6 17. Rxa4 $18 {1-0 (31) Grischuk,A (2736) -Riazantsev,A (2661) Moscow 2009}  ) 7. O-O Bg7 8. Re1 O-O {This position has a lot in common with the structure from the 5...c6 sideline that we examined in Chapter 2. The main difference is that White cannot provoke concessions by attacking the e-pawn with Bg5, so he needs to play more patiently in this case.} 9. Bb3 {is a good first step. We prophylactically retreat the bishop to a safer square, while also keeping an option to play c2-c4 in some cases.} Be6 {This seems to be Black's best strategy. He plans to retreat the knight to c7 and make a favourable exchange of bishops. Black has a couple of notable alternatives, as well.} ( Bf5 {is a sensible continuation, as well, as the bishop is located actively here.} 10. Nd2 {It makes a bit more sense to strengthen the d4-e5 axis with Ndf3 and c2-c3} ( {than weaken it for the sake of grabbing more space with} 11. c4 {After} Nc7 12. Nc3 Nd7 {Black solves most of his problems since} 13. Ng4 {is well met by} Bxg4 14. Qxg4 Nf6 15. Qh4 b5 $1 16. Be3 a5 $11  ) Nd7 11. Ndf3 Nxe5 12. Nxe5 a5 13. a4 Qc7 14. c3 $14 {White is fully in control as Black cannot undermine his centre in a good way. In the following GM game, White demonstrated central superiority when Black tried to open the position prematurely.} Rad8 15. Qf3 Qc8 16. h3 Be6 17. Bd2 c5 $6 18. c4 $1 Nb4 19. d5 Bf5 20. g4 Bd7 21. Bc3 $16 {1-0 (56) Shi