ine.} 11. d5 Nd4 12. hxg6 $1 {With the king on g8, this inclusion is very strong.} ( 13. Nxd4 exd4 14. Bxd4 Bxd4 15. Qxd4 e5 16. dxe6  ) Nxf3+ {This exchange is virtually forced} ( {since the attempt to transpose into the main line with} hxg6 13. Nxd4 exd4 14. Bxd4 Bxd4 15. Qxd4 e5 {is futile here in the view of} 16. Qe3 $40 {when White will have a strong attack on the h-file.}  ) 13. gxf3 hxg6 14. Bd3 Bf5 {This has all been seen in Fuatai, F (2015) -Dive, R (2375) Auckland 2011 ½-½ (25) and now} 15. Rg1 $5 $146 {would have highlighted Black's problems with the g6-pawn. White's plan is simply either to connect the rooks for the kingside attack with Qd2, 0-0-0, or, in case of} Qd7 16. a4 $1 $16 {when the knight on b6 would be in an awkward situation.}  ) 10. d5 Nd4 11. Nxd4 exd4 12. Bxd4 Bxd4 13. Qxd4 e5 14. dxe6 O-O {This is Black's idea. He will eventually return the e6-pawn and oppose the powerful white queen with ...Qf6. However, White obtains a superior endgame with only two possible results with a precise sequence:} 15. h5 Qf6 16. Qxf6 Rxf6 17. e7 Re6+ 18. Kd2 Rxe7 19. hxg6 hxg6 20. Bd3 {Black did not have much choice up until now and neither does he on his next move as the g6-pawn is quite weak.} Bf5 21. Rh6 $1 {An important move, keeping the initiative in the endgame on the account of Rah1 next. Black has a couple of defensive options, but the underlying problems in his position: the weak g-pawn, the sidelined knight on b6 and the exposed king remain in either case.} Rf8 ( Rg7 22. Rah1 Kf7 23. R6h4 $36 {In this line, the rook is very passive on g7 and Black struggles with his piece coordination.}  ) 22. f3 Rh7 {Trying to neutralize White's initiative on the h-file, only to run into more serious problems on the e-file.} ( {More solid was} Kf7 23. Rah1 Rg8 {but White still has a strong initiative after} 24. b3 {etc.}  ) 23. Rxh7 Kxh7 24. Re1 $1 Kg7 $2 {This loses outright.} ( Rf7 {was called for, when} 25. Re8 $16 {keeps White firmly in the driver's seat.}  ) 2