{[%evp 0,37,57,31,32,39,72,72,80,51,53,44,70,65,69,40,80,53,53,37,31,58,23,23, 23,31,26,5,31,21,18,18,8,7,7,-1,4,-4,-4,-25]} 1. e4 d5 {Similarly to the Alekhine Defense, the Scandinavian Defence is a somewhat provocative opening in which Black surrenders central control early, planning to counter-attack white pawn centre later. Another similarity to the Alekhine Defence is that Black develops a piece to d5-square on move 2, only, in this case, it is the queen (except in Chapter 15) as opposed to the knight in the Alekhine. After the standard} 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 {Black has three main queen retreats that will be examined in Chapters 9 through 14. In this chapter, we will look at the most popular move} Qa5 {The queen is fairly safe from attacks on this square. White usually takes space in the centre with 4.d4 here, but I suggest a less common, yet quite an interesting and possibly venomous alternative} 4. Bc4 $5 {Grandmaster Nigel Short gets the credit for popularizing this variation. The idea is to continue d2-d3 and put the bishop on d2, threatening to trap the black queen. A similar plan is available to White in the main line with the pawn on d4, but the main difference is that here the d-pawn will not be exposed on d4. Thus, Black's typical counterplay connected to ...Bg4, ... Nc6 and ...0-0-0 is largely ineffective against White's slightly passive, but extremely solid central structure.} Nf6 5. d3 {At this point, Black has many playable options. We will analyze the three most popular ones.} c6 $5 {is the most common move in the position. Black prepares the c7-square for the queen (in the view of our Bd2, Nd5 threat) and takes control of the important squares b5 and d5.} ( Bg4 {is a typical move in the Scandinavian, trying to provoke weakening of White's position with f2-f3. I believe that we should not allow that at the moment, so} 6. Nge2 $5 {is the preferred move. We are simply completing our kingside development as the pin on the knight is not particularly problematic.} e6 {The most natural developing move.} ( Nc6 {is the alternative plan, going for queenside castling. We can see here how this plan is much less effective with the pawn on d3 instead on d4, where it becomes an immediate target.} 7. Bd2 Qh5 {The queen had to cross over to the other side of the board because a5 was not safe for it any more. However, such manoeuvres are rarely a good sign in the opening stage. At the very least, White wins a couple of tempi to complete his development.} 8. f3 {We play this weakening move in obviously better circumstances than on the previous move.} Bd7 9. Be3 $1 {In this line, White plans to castle queenside where the king will be safer, but also because it would make black queen more exposed on the kingside.} ( {A worse option is} 10. O-O e5 11. Be3 O-O-O 12. a3 Qg6 13. Qe1 $132  ) O-O-O ( {Now} e5 {is met by} 10. Qd2 O-O-O 11. O-O-O $14 {and black queen feels awkward on the kingside.}  ) 10. Qd2 e6 11. O-O-O Qa5 {Black can swing the queen over back to a5 now that this square is safe again, but such time-wasting has its price. White has better development and the black queen is not particularly happy there anyway. An effective plan for White is} 12. a3 Kb8 13. Kb1 Bd6 14. Nc1 $1 Qf5 15. Nb3 $14  ) ( Nbd7 {is another logical developing move. Now, it is useful to insert} 7. h3 {to determine the position of black bishop. In case he keeps the pin with} Bh5 {the h5-square would not be available to the queen any more} ( Bf5 {has been played in Hansen, E (2629) -Pruijssers,R (2536) chess.com INT 2018 1-0 (64) , but it could have been refuted by} 8. b4 $1 Qxb4 9. Rb1 Qd6 10. Nb5 Qb6 11. Be3 c5 12. Nbd4 $18  ) {so White would get a solid edge with} 8. Bd2 e6 9. O-O c6 10. Nd5 Qd8 11. Ndf4 $14 {winning the bishop pair.}  ) 7. O-O Bd6 {This is the most active move, threatening 8...Qh5.} ( Nbd7 {is again best met with} 8. h3 Bxe2 9. Qxe2 Qe5 10. a4 Bd6 11. Qxe5 Nxe5 12. Bb3 $14 {and White would have a pleasant advantage in the endgame due to the potent bishop pair and a flexible pawn structure. One sample line is} a6 13. Be3 Ng6 14. g3 Ne7 15. f4 h5 16. Kg2 $14  ) {However, White can interfere with this plan with} 8. Nb5 $1 {which will net us the bishop pair.} a6 9. Bd2 Qb6 10. Nxd6+ cxd6 11. Be3 Qc7 12. f3 Bf5 13. a4 $14 {with a promising position thanks to the bishop pair and many active possibilities.}  ) ( Bf5 {is a typical move in many similar variations, but the bishop is much less effective on this diagonal compared to the similar positions with the pawn on d4. Anyway, White can proceed with his plan} 6. Bd2 $1 e6 {This looks risky, but it is actually possible.} ( Nbd7 $2 {loses outright to} 7. Qf3 $1 e6 8. Qxb7 Rb8 9. Qc6 Rxb2 10. Nd5 Qc5 11. Qxc5 Nxc5 12. Ne3 $1 {This backward move is the key. White gets a technically winning endgame with equal material.} Rb8 ( Bg6 13. Bb3 Nxb3 14. axb3 $18  ) 13. Nxf5 exf5 14. Nf3 $18  ) 7. Nf3 ( 8. Nd5 {is tempting, but the classical combination} Qc5 9. Bb4 Qc6 10. Bb5 $2 {does not work here in the view of} Bxb4+ 11. c3 Nxd5 12. Bxc6+ Nxc6 13. cxb4 Ndxb4 $15 {when Black gets too much material and piece play for the queen.}  ) Bb4 {This is a typical way that Black solve the Nc3-d5 issue. However, if we compare the position after} 8. a3 Bxc3 9. Bxc3 Qb6 {to a very similar theoretical position with the pawn on d4 instead, we can see several benefits for White in the 'Short variation'. Firstly, the d4-pawn is not obstructing the dark-squared bishop, so it is much more active here. Secondly, d3-pawn limits the influence of f5-bishop. White enjoys a very pleasant advantage in the middlegame, as in the following game} 10. Qd2 Nbd7 11. h3 Bg6 12. O-O O-O 13. Rfe1 $16 {Peng,H (2370) -Bilguun, S (2478) Xingtai 2019 ½-½ (25) . White could have obtained more space on the queenside with the thematic b2-b4, etc.}  ) 6. Bd2 {This move is played not only to expel the queen from an active position but also to keep the option of queenside castling open.} Qc7 {Naturally, 