{[%evp 0,57,5,21,41,45,62,52,70,69,69,56,79,10,22,27,51,15,77,32,71,94,43,59, 52,40,38,41,42,42,85,72,92,89,14,27,27,34,19,17,30,27,26,24,19,6,6,6,32,40,56, 57,57,53,51,54,54,54,54,30]} 1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qd6 {Nowadays, this queen's retreat is perhaps even more popular than 3...Qa5 since many strong players have played this way. Strong GM Sergey Tiviakov has made a big contribution to the development of this variation for Black and White needs to be very well prepared to obtain an opening advantage against it. The idea behind the move is the keep the queen on an active and less exposed square from where it keeps the pressure on the d4-pawn. In some cases, this pressure can be increased with ...Nc6, ...0-0-0. Now the Bc4, d3 plan does not work that well as black queen is not exposed on a5, so we should continue} 4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 {In this 'tabiya', Black has many possible development directions. We shall study the four most popular ones: 5.. .a6, 5...c6, 5...Bg4 and 5...g6. In this chapter, our focus will be on the historically most popular continuation} a6 {which leads to sharp play as Black takes control of the b5-square and then typically completes queenside development with ...Bg4, ... Nc6, and ...0-0-0.} 6. g3 {Among many alternatives, this move has crystalized as the best one. Since Black plans to castle queenside, White develops the bishop to the long diagonal so that b7-square becomes vulnerable in some cases. Another important point behind g2-g3 is that we can win a tempo for development by attacking the queen with Bf4 in some cases.} Bg4 {The best move in the position for Black as he completes his development in the quickest possible way, pins the knight and prepares ...Nc6 with pressure on the centre.} ( {The alternative is} b5 {planning to oppose opponent's bishop on the long diagonal. However, this plan is positionally dubious for Black since White can make a typical breakthrough on the queenside with a4 and create new weaknesses. Black usually 